# Ex2: Scatter plot with ggplot2

## -2.5

```{r}
#| echo: false
# Relabel soph variable
df_soph_relabeled <- df %>% 
  mutate(soph = case_when(soph == "1" ~ "Sophomore",
                           soph == "0" ~ "Non-Sophomore"),
         soph = factor(soph))

# Print to confirm
print(df_soph_relabeled)

# Create Plot
ggplot2::ggplot(df_soph_relabeled, aes(x = priGPA, y = missed)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue", size = 2) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red") +
  facet_wrap(~soph) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Relationship between Prior GPA and Classes Missed",
       x = "Prior GPA", y = "Classes Missed",
       caption = "Moderator: Sophomore Status")
```

Insights: The Regression Lines, which are the red lines, demonstrate a downward slope. The downward slope exemplifies the idea that students with higher GPA's, better performing, miss less classes and show higher attendance. There is also a dense cluster of data points towards the bottom end of classes missed as the prior GPA increases. This can show that students with higher GPA's are less likely to miss classes

# **Ex 3**: Understand barplots (dodge vs. stack vs. faceted)

## -3.3

```{r}
#| echo: false
# 3.1 Barplot for the count of ACT scores
# Converting ACT to a factor allows ggplot to treat each score as a distinct category
ggplot(df_soph_relabeled, aes(x = factor(ACT))) +
  geom_bar(fill = "steelblue") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of ACT Scores",
       x = "ACT Score",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

# 3.2 Creating the three bar charts for 'final' score
# 1. Dodged Bar Chart
ggplot(df_soph_relabeled, aes(x = factor(ACT), y = final, fill = soph)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Final Scores by ACT (Dodged)", x = "ACT", y = "Final Score")

# 2. Stacked Bar Chart (Default)
ggplot(df_soph_relabeled, aes(x = factor(ACT), y = final, fill = soph)) +
  geom_col(position = "stack") +
  labs(title = "Final Scores by ACT (Stacked)", x = "ACT", y = "Final Score")

# 3. Faceted Bar Chart
ggplot(df_soph_relabeled, aes(x = factor(ACT), y = final, fill = soph)) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~soph) +
  labs(title = "Final Scores by ACT (Faceted)", x = "ACT", y = "Final Score")

```

Insights: After evaluating the three charts, I believe the dodged bar chart accurately describes the data because we see a side by side comparison of the ACT scores for the sophomores and non-sophomores along with accurate information along the y axis. The faceted bar chart allows for easy comparison between both groups without any overlapping.

# **Ex 4**: Barplots with ACT averages (Understand Bar plots)

## -4.4

```{r}
#| echo: false
df_soph_relabled_summarized <- df_soph_relabeled %>%
  group_by(soph, ACT) %>% 
  summarise(final_avg = mean(final), n = n(), .groups = "drop") 

# Use final_avg for Y-axis
ggplot(df_soph_relabled_summarized, aes(x = factor(ACT), y = final_avg, fill = soph)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Average Final Score by ACT and Sophomore Status (Dodged)",
       x = "ACT Score", y = "Average Final Score") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(df_soph_relabled_summarized, aes(x = factor(ACT), y = final_avg, fill = soph)) +
  geom_col(position = "stack") +
  labs(title = "Average Final Score by ACT and Sophomore Status (Stacked)",
       x = "ACT Score", y = "Average Final Score") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(df_soph_relabled_summarized, aes(x = factor(ACT), y = final_avg, fill = soph)) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~soph) +
  labs(title = "Average Final Score by ACT and Sophomore Status (Faceted)",
       x = "ACT Score", y = "Average Final Score") +
  theme_minimal()
```

Insights: I believe the Faceted bar chart accurately describes the data because it shows a direct visual comparison of the average final exam scores without confusion. From the dodged bar chart in Q3.2, I would trust the one from Q4.2 because it proves to be easily understood, labeled properly and precise. The main difference in the relationships between ACT and final scores shown in both groups is that one focuses on total volume and the other on average performance. The average is much more precise for analysis while the other is a cumulative contribution.

# **Ex 5**: Boxplot vs. correct barplot 

## -5.3

```{r}
#| echo: false
ggplot(df_soph_relabeled, aes(x = factor(ACT), y = final, fill = soph)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.3)
```

Insights: The differences between the box plot here and the bar plot I chose from Q4 (faceted bar chart) is the cleanliness and easily readable pot. The box plot here is somewhat messy, unorganized and proves to be a lot going on, while the faceted bar chart from above is easy to analyze and organized. I prefer the faceted bar chart from above because it is easier to analyze and interpret. From the box plot here, the differences in patterns of relationships between ACT and final scores are that there is a positive correlation while still including variability. As for any ACT score, there is a range of final scores.

